children.text: There are cold water service pipes that have been installed in areas where they will be heated.
‘Drinking water that is not intentionally heated must be delivered at a temperature of less than 40 degrees Celsius’ .
The relevant Australian Standard AS 3500.1 Plumbing and Drainage, requires that

‘To prevent any unreasonable rise in the temperature of the cold water delivered to fixtures located within a building, pipes and fittings installed above the ground should be protected against the heating effects of solar radiation or other heat sources’ .
The Victorian Building Authority (VBA) has provided a Technical Solution Sheet 5.05 which provides assistance in achieving compliance with AS 3500.1 by suggesting the following;
Avoid installing cold water piping in ceiling spaces where the roof coverings are a dark colour and where there is limited flow-through ventilation
Avoid installing cold water piping directly below roof coverings
Avoid installing cold water piping in external cavity walls facing north or west, or at least
keep pipe-work away from the external wall cladding. Keep pipes running horizontally and near the base of wall cavities’ .

There should either be insulation installed to all cold-water piping in these areas, or alternatively these pipes should be relocated to ensure compliance with the Plumbing Regulations and Australian Standards.
